  "prompt": "What does the GDP per capita represent?",
  "response": "GDP per capita represents the economic output of a country divided by its population. It is calculated by taking the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of a country, which measures the total value of all goods and services produced over a specific time period, and dividing it by the number of people living in that country. \n\nThis metric is often used as an indicator of a country's standard of living and economic health, as it provides a rough estimate of the average economic productivity and prosperity of its citizens. A higher GDP per capita generally suggests a higher standard of living and better access to goods and services, while a lower GDP per capita may indicate poverty or economic challenges. However, it is important to note that GDP per capita does not account for income distribution within a country, so it may not fully reflect inequalities in wealth and living conditions among the population.",
